461. JAMA. 1978 Sep 29;240(14):1542-7. doi: 10.1001/jama.240.14.1542.

A modern view of the surgical treatment of peripheral arterial disease.

Miller DC, Griepp RB.

As life expectancy increases, more patients will harbor atherosclerotic 
conditions that portend disability and death. Due basically to a communication 
gap, sizable numbers of these patients who stand to benefit from vascular 
reconstruction are not being referred or are being referred too late to vascular 
surgeons. Vascular surgery currently can save limbs, extend productivity and 
life expectancy, ameliorate hypertension, and prevent stroke more reliably and 
with less risk than ever before. As the subspeciality of vascular surgery has 
matured, has incorporated additional fellowship training, and now approaches 
potential recognition in some yet to be determined form by The American Board of 
Surgery, it is incumbent on general physicians and vascular surgeons alike to 
develop appropriate channels that can transmit clinical concepts, educational 
information, and clinical results, as well as refer patients.

